log: Create a Wayang plan that finds all the purchases in the household appliances file for purchases made in october 2025. It should only include purchases for organisation which have more than 10 departments, also return the creditor name of these purchases as well as the price and the purchase line. Output in a textfile.

log: From the "household appliances" file, find all purchase records with purchase dates in October 2025 (i.e., from 2025-10-01 through 2025-10-31 inclusive). Restrict results to purchases belonging to organisations that have more than 10 departments (as indicated in the same file). For each matching purchase record, return the creditor name, the price, and the purchase line. Write all resulting records to a text file.

log.thoughts: Selected factpurchases for purchase records (invoice_date, invoice_line_descr, invoice_line_price, creditor_id, organisation_id). Selected department to count departments per organisation (department.organisation_id) to filter organisations with more than 10 departments. Selected creditor to obtain creditor.name for each purchase. Selected household_appliances text file because the plan must find purchases that match entries from that file.

steps.detailed_description: Load the following input sources: (a) factpurchases JDBC table with all columns (purchase_id, organisation_id, department_id, creditor_id, invoice_id, invoice_date, invoice_line_no, invoice_line_descr, invoice_line_price); (b) creditor JDBC table with all columns (creditor_id, name, creditor_type); (c) department JDBC table with all columns (department_id, organisation_id, name, operation_center, esyn); (d) household_appliances text file read line-by-line (each line is an appliance keyword such as 'Komfur', 'Håndvask', 'Ovn'). Output: four loaded datasets to be consumed by downstream steps.

Perform three unary preparations from the inputs: (A) From department dataset, group by organisation_id and count distinct department_id to produce organisation_dept_counts with columns (organisation_id, dept_count). Then filter to keep only organisations where dept_count > 10 producing eligible_organisations (organisation_id). (B) From factpurchases dataset, filter rows where invoice_date >= '2025-10-01' AND invoice_date <= '2025-10-31' to produce purchases_oct2025. (C) From household_appliances text lines, normalize/trimming lines to produce a list of appliance keywords; then filter purchases_oct2025 by keeping only rows where invoice_line_descr contains (case-insensitive) at least one of these appliance keywords, producing appliance_purchases_oct2025. Outputs: eligible_organisations and appliance_purchases_oct2025.

Join appliance_purchases_oct2025 (from step 2) with eligible_organisations (from step 2) on organisation_id to keep only purchases belonging to organisations with dept_count > 10. Then join the resulting filtered purchases with creditor table (from step 1) on creditor_id to attach creditor.name. Output: joined_filtered_purchases containing at least columns (creditor.name, invoice_line_price, invoice_line_descr, purchase_id, organisation_id).

Project the final columns: creditor name (creditor.name), price (invoice_line_price), and purchase line (invoice_line_descr) from joined_filtered_purchases. Write all resulting records to the requested text file (one record per line, formatted as desired).

log.thoughts: Loaded all four inputs, computed organisation department counts and filtered purchases by October 2025 and by appliance keywords, then filtered purchases to eligible organisations, joined creditor names, and wrote the selected three columns to output. Four steps keep the plan compact and logically separated (inputs, unary preparation/filters, binary joins, output).
